               Thirdly, That way of Prayer wherein we may join with greater Faith and Aſſurance, is the moſt ſolemn, and fitteſt to be us'd in publick Worſhip: But this we may better do in a Form than without it; and therefore that is the beſt way to ſecure the Reverence and Solemnity of publick Worſhip. That Faith and a good Aſſurance of being heard are neceſſary Ingredients of an effectual Prayer, St. James hath plainly told us; for he wills all that would obtain any thing at the Hands of God, to ask in Faith, nothing wavering;
Jam. 1.6, 7, 8. for he that wavers is like a wave of the ſea, driven with the wind, and toſſed: Let not that man think that he ſhall receive any thing of the Lord.
Matth. 18.19. A double minded man is unſtable in all his ways. And our Bleſſed Saviour hath told us, That we muſt agree, and join together in what we ask, before it will be given us. So that a joynt Conſent and Agreement in our Prayers, offer'd up in Faith, without wrath and doubting, is the beſt means of procuring to us the Succeſs of them.
